Project Report 3
ABSTRACT
This report describes features of the final project on Network Management
and it is divided into four chapters. The idea of the project of the course is to
develop a dynamic website using Application Programming Interface (API)
to automate network tasks of Fault Management, Configuration
Management, Accounting Management, Performance Management, and
Security Management. Chapter One summarizes the working of the Fault
Management Page. Chapter two describes the features of the Configuration
management page. Chapter three Describes the Accounting management
page and chapter four gives an overview of the Performance Management
page and Chapter five describes the Security Management page of my
website.

HOME PAGE

Project Report 6
CHAPTER -1
Fault Management:
Fault Management is a critical part of network monitoring. It gives the user a
central place to receive, acknowledge, and organize all important notifications
from devices on the network.
The diagnostic information can be retrieved directly by proactively querying the
information from the MIB using SNMP, it can also be acquired simply by listening
for messages sent from the agents in the form of SNMP Traps and Notifications.
These messages are also known as alarms. The manager (NMS) defines an alarm
based on a series of events. The agents that have the capability to send diagnostic
information in these formats must be told where to send the information.
In this project we use the SNMP log file to show the time log of the Interface up
(green), Interface down (red) events. The network devices used include both
Ethernet switches (192.168.1.1 and 192.168.1.2). To navigate to the Fault
Management page to see the trap events for both the switches, go to the Network
Management Home page and click on the Fault management on the Navigation
tab. It displays the most recent 50 events of both Ethernet switches with status
showing link Up event and down event.

Project Report 8
CHAPTER -2
Configuration Management Page
In Configuration Management we display the device configuration information and
system information. Using network configuration, we set a value to a MIB or to a
group of MIBs to perform a certain configuration function. To navigate to the
Configuration Management page, go to the Home page and click on the
Configuration Management Tab.
A routing table is a set of rules, often viewed in a table format, that is used to
determine where data packets traveling over an Internet Protocol (IP) network will
be directed. To get the IP routing Information select the IP Address from the Drop-
down menu and click Submit.
Project Report 9
The ARP table is used to maintain a correlation between each MAC address and its
corresponding IP address. It is used to determine the destination MAC addresses of
the network nodes, as well as the VLANs and ports from where the nodes are
reached. To access the ARP table data navigate to the ARP on the configuration
management page and select an IP address from the drop-down and hit submit.
Project Report 10
A MAC address table is used on Ethernet switches to determine where to forward
traffic on a LAN. It contains address information that the switch uses to forward
traffic between ports. To navigate to the MAC address table, go to the
configuration management page select the Ip address and VLAN from the drop-
down and click submit.
Project Report 11
CDP is a Cisco proprietary protocol that is used for collecting directly connected
neighbor device information like hardware, software, device name details, etc. To
navigate to the CDP Table, go to the Configuration Management page and select
the IP address from the drop-down and click submit.
Project Report 12
CHAPTER -3
Accounting Management
On this page, we generate an account usage report, showing the total and average
usage time of each account. To get to the account usage report navigate to the
Account Management tab on the navigation tab. The input data is obtained from
events of the Syslog files. Events are activities on the system, including user login
attempts, commands to access the system information, changes to the system
configuration, status (state transition) of system configuration, etc. Syslog is a tool
to collect and archive the event logs on the system
Project Report 13
CHAPTER -4
Performance Management
On this page, we generate the Network Throughput report, System load Report,
and RTT report. To navigate to the performance management page, click on the tab
on the navigation bar.
In-Network Throughput report we run MRTG to develop a web site to track the
incoming and outgoing traffic of Ethernet switches 192.168.1.1, 192.168.1.2, and
192.168.1.3. To navigate to the Mrtg output go to the performance management
and click on the link to the switches.
Project Report 14
In System load Report we analyze the System Load (also known as
system utilization) of Linux05. To get the report to navigate to the performance
management page and select the start date, end date, and report Type in the table
and click submit.
Project Report 15
RTT report is Task Automation performance test with ping. It shows the results of
the round-trip time (RTT) and standard deviation of RTT. To get the report to
navigate to the performance management page and select the link to the RTT
report.
Project Report 16
CHAPTER -5
In Security Management we generate an intrusion report showing the number of
intrusion attempts from each IP source. To navigate to the security management
page, click on the tab on the navigation bar. The report shows the different IP
addresses and Intrusion count for each Ip address.
